University Course Description 
Introduction to computer hardwa

ourse Description 
Introduction to computer hardware, logic elements and Boolean algebra, computer arithmetic, the 
central processing unit, assembly language programming, input/output, and memory. 
 
ii. 
Prerequisites and Credits:  
Programming Concepts COP 2510, General Physics II PHY 2049 or PHY 2054 or equivalent. 
Credits: 3 
 
iii.

Getting to Know Your Classmate

labus Quiz and the 
Getting to Know Your Classmates discussion assignment. Students who do not complete 
the first week’s activities by the due date run the risk of being dropped from the course. 
 
iv. 
Course Objectives  
To study the basic organization and architecture of digital computers. Discussions will include 
numbering systems, digital logic, CPU, instruction set architecture, assembly programming, memory 
hierarchy, Input/Output, operating system and etc. Such knowledge leads to bette

ting system and etc. Such knowledge leads to better understanding and 
utilization of digital computers, and can be used in the design and application of computer systems or 
as foundation for more advanced computer-related studies.

vi. 
Student Learning Outcomes 
Towards the end of this course, students should be able to:  
• 
Understand and apply the basic concepts of number representations, computer arithmetic, and 
Boolean algebra. 
• 
Understand the operation of basic logic elements 
• 
Design simple combinational and sequential circuits using basic logic elements. 
• 
Understand special-purpose codes. 
• 
Underst

• 
Understand special-purpose codes. 
• 
Understand the basic organization of a Central Processing Unit and its operation during execution 
of machine language instructions through a simple architecture. 
• 
Create simple assembly languages programs  
• 
Understand different types of memory and become familiar with the role of memory hierarchy in 
computer organization. 
• 
Understand basic input/output in simple computer architectures.  
• 
Understand the role of operating systems and embedde

derstand the role of operating systems and embedded systems in computing systems.
